          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       World’s oldest and functioning company  
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Kongo Gumi’s story begins in 578 AD, when Buddhism was taking root in Japan. Prince Shōtoku wanted a proper Buddhist temple built. So, he invited Shigemitsu Kongo, a master carpenter from Baekje, in modern-day Korea, to construct the Shitennō-ji Temple, Japan’s first Buddhist temple. That project launched a legacy that would <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-07-2025-1-last-over-1400-years" target="_blank">last over 1,400 years</a>.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/showa-depression-kongo-gumi-tragedy.jpg" alt="The Showa Depression in the 1920s was a challenging period, leading to the tragic suicide of Kongo Haruichi, the 37th leader" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
          The Showa Depression in the 1920s was a challenging period, leading to the tragic suicide of Kongo Haruichi, the 37th leader. Credits: Kongo Gumi</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Kongo Gumi's expertise in traditional woodworking and joinery techniques made them vital to preserving Japan’s cultural heritage. The family-run business was passed down through more than 40 generations. But things took a turn in the 1980s. Japan’s economic bubble encouraged reckless borrowing, and Kongo Gumi, eager to diversify, expanded into real estate and development. 
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           When the bubble burst in the 1990s, the company was saddled with crushing debt. By 2006, it had accumulated about $343M and was forced to file for bankruptcy. That same year, it was absorbed by the Takamatsu Construction Group. The family’s direct ownership ended, but the company, still called Kongo Gumi, survived, continuing to restore temples, pagodas, and other national sites. Ironically, what centuries of upheaval couldn’t kill, modern debt almost did.
            </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>


