      <mj-column>
       <mj-spacer height="18px"></mj-spacer>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
       1,100 years on tap
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     
Tucked along the River Shannon in Athlone, Ireland, Sean’s Bar holds the title of the oldest pub in the country and arguably the oldest continuously operating bar in the world, <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-07-2025-2-dating-back-to-900-ad" target="_blank">dating back to 900 AD</a>. Legend has it that Luain Mac Luighdeach, its founder, first opened an unlicensed drinking spot near a key fording point on the river, making an ideal stop for travelers looking for rest, news, and a pint.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/seans-bar-worlds-best-mind-blowing-lonely-planet-listed.jpg" alt="Sean’s bar is listed in both “25 of the Most Incredible Bars in the World” and “50 Bars to Blow Your Mind” by Lonely Planet" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
          Sean’s bar is listed in both “25 of the Most Incredible Bars in the World” and “50 Bars to Blow Your Mind” by Lonely Planet. Credits: Sean’s Bar</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           In the 1970s, renovations revealed that 9th-century wattle-and-daub walls and old coins were discovered inside the walls of the bar. These were carbon-dated and verified by the National Museum of Ireland, which supports its claim to being over 1,100 years old. Currently, the place has even earned itself a position in the Guinness Book of World Records as the oldest public house. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       Inside, Sean’s Bar remains every bit the classic Irish pub, with whitewashed walls, wood beams, ancient stone floors, a well-stocked whiskey bar, live music, and pints of Guinness. It has even turned its age into a unique selling point and sells bottled whiskeys and merchandise themed around its legendary history. It attracts visitors from all over the world, not just for the drinks, but for witnessing the living history lesson that it is.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="4px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
      A centuries-old business of alchemy 
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     Zildjian is not just one of the oldest companies in the world, but it's also one of the most iconic brands in modern music. Founded in 1623 in Constantinople, now Istanbul, within the Ottoman Empire, it has been crafting cymbals for <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-07-2025-3-over-400-years" target="_blank">over 400 years</a>, passing down its secret alloy recipe through 15 generations of the same family.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/zildjian-cymbals-in-symphonies-rock-marching-jingles.jpg" alt="Zildjian cymbals have seen ubiquitous presence in music, whether in symphonies or rock anthems, marching bands, or even advertising jingles" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
           Zildjian cymbals have seen ubiquitous presence in music, whether in symphonies or rock anthems, marching bands, or even advertising jingles. Credits: Zildjian</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         While attempting to turn base metals into gold, Avedis I, an Armenian alchemist in the Ottoman court, accidentally discovered a bronze alloy with a unique combination of durability and musical resonance. Sultan Osman II was impressed and he gave him the name “Zildjian,” from zil (cymbal) and dji (maker of). And thus, the Zildjian legacy was born, supplying cymbals first to Janissary military bands, then mosques, palaces, and eventually classical orchestras.
            </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
     In 1929, Avedis Zildjian III, a 9th-generation descendant, moved the company to the US to meet growing demand from Western classical and jazz musicians. He set up shop in Massachusetts, turning the ancient family craft into a modern, industrial-scale global business. The company chose to adapt and improvise, scaling up production, standardizing cymbal sizes, and tailoring their sound to match the evolving needs of jazz drummers and big bands. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
   Craigie and Debbie Zildjian lead the company, the first women to helm the business in its 400-year history, proving once again that legacy doesn’t mean standing still.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
